    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Global expectations on Trump’s return</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-17-1.png" alt="Global expectations on Trump’s return" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">A recent study and poll by Oxford University and the European Council on Foreign Relations show a striking divide in global expectations for Trump’s second presidency. The most significant contrast is seen among the traditional US allies such as the UK, South Korea, and the EU, who were among the most skeptical. Countries like India, China, Brazil, Saudi Arabia, and Russia are more optimistic about his presidency.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4; filter: blur(5px);">This study demonstrates that the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-17-01-2025-h1-1-west-is-divided" target="_blank">West is divided</a> over Trump’s second term to a point where we cannot call “the West” as a single geopolitical entity. The big challenge for Europeans is to find their place in a more à la carte, zero-sum world. Most countries seem very optimistic about Trump’s return and believe he will bring peace to Ukraine and the Middle East. The study also establishes that the Trump-led US is viewed as a global superpower and that the EU has the ability to act on equal terms with the US and China.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
